# .dockerignore
# Build-context exclusions shared by every Dockerfile under docker/ (Infra Phase 5's docker/apex/Dockerfile and Infra Phase 6's docker/kali/Dockerfile) — keeps secrets, VCS metadata, caches, tests, and raw knowledge corpora out of the image build context.
#
# This file governs what the Docker CLI sends to the daemon as the build
# context when building from the repository root, regardless of which
# Dockerfile is selected via `-f`:
#   docker build -f docker/apex/Dockerfile -t apex:phase5 .
#   docker build -f docker/kali/Dockerfile -t apex-kali:phase6 .
#
# It does NOT, by itself, decide what ends up *in* either image — each
# Dockerfile's COPY instructions are additionally selective (they name exact
# files/directories, they never do a blanket `COPY . .`). Both layers matter:
# this file keeps large/sensitive things out of the context sent to the
# daemon in the first place; each Dockerfile's explicit COPY list keeps the
# image itself minimal even for things that *do* reach the daemon.
# docker/kali/Dockerfile does not COPY Knowledge/*/compiled/ at all (the
# Kali tool-service appliance carries no knowledge corpora, see
# docs/kali-container.md) — only docker/apex/Dockerfile does.
#
# Required-file guarantee: pyproject.toml, uv.lock, memfabric/, apex_host/,
# apex_tool_service/, docker/ (this whole directory, both Dockerfiles), and
# Knowledge/*/compiled/ are NEVER excluded below — every pattern here was
# checked against that list before being added.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Version control
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.git
.github
.gitignore

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Python virtual environments and caches — the image builds its own venv
# from uv.lock; a locally-created .venv must never be copied in verbatim
# (wrong platform, may contain dev-only packages, defeats reproducibility).
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.venv
venv
env
__pycache__
*.py[cod]
*$py.class
.pytest_cache
.mypy_cache
.ruff_cache
.coverage
htmlcov
*.egg-info
build
dist

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Secrets and environment files — excluded so a locally created .env (or any
# VPN credential bundle) can never be baked into an image by accident.
#
# `.env.*` matches `.env.example` too (it is a glob, not an exact-name
# match like Git's `.env` entry can be) — the explicit `!.env.example`
# negation below restores it. Neither Dockerfile actually COPies
# `.env.example` into an image today (both use selective, explicit COPY
# instructions — see each Dockerfile's own comments), so this negation is
# not currently load-bearing for image contents, but it keeps the build
# *context* itself from silently excluding a file a future test, doc
# build, or Dockerfile change might reasonably expect to find (Infra
# Phase 8's own explicit requirement: "Do not use a broad `.env*` rule
# that accidentally excludes `.env.example`, unless explicitly negated").
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.env
.env.local
.env.*.local
.env.*
!.env.example
*.ovpn
secrets/
*.pem
*.key

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# IDE / OS artifacts
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.vscode
.idea
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
*.log

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local run output — ephemeral, never a build input. The image creates its
# own empty, writable /app/run_reports at build time (see Dockerfile).
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
run_reports

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Tests — not required at runtime; excluding them keeps the build context
# smaller and guarantees no accidental `COPY tests` could ever ship test
# doubles or fixtures into a production image.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
tests

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Documentation and historical artifacts — not required at runtime.
# docs/ contains only Markdown design documents; APEX reads no file under
# docs/ at import time or runtime. README.md and CLAUDE.md are similarly
# unnecessary inside the image (they document the *repository*, not
# something the running application consults).
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
docs
README.md
CLAUDE.md
APEX-Nexus-Unified-Architecture-Detailed.md
Makefile

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Examples — a small (12 KB) memfabric demo script (examples/smoke_run.py),
# not imported by apex_host and not needed to run any APEX CLI.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
examples

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Knowledge/ — raw vendored corpora and downloaded datasets (~4.3 GB on
# disk; verified via `du -sh` during this phase's investigation). The
# Dockerfile's COPY instructions pull in ONLY the four `*/compiled/`
# subdirectories (~49 MB total) by exact, explicit path — everything listed
# below is excluded from the build context entirely so it can never reach
# the daemon, regardless of what the Dockerfile does or does not COPY.
#
# NOTE ON CASING: the tracked directory is `Knowledge/` (capital K) — see
# the Dockerfile's own comment on this. Patterns below match that exact
# casing since Docker's dockerignore matching is case-sensitive on the
# Linux daemon this normally builds against, even though the local checkout
# filesystem (macOS/APFS) is case-insensitive.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Raw vendored payload-technique repositories (GTFOBins, LOLBAS,
# PayloadsAllTheThings) and the SecLists wordlist corpus (1.9 GB alone).
Knowledge/payload_db/SecLists
Knowledge/payload_db/PayloadsAllTheThings
Knowledge/payload_db/GTFOBins
Knowledge/payload_db/LOLBAS

# Raw threat-intelligence datasets: NVD CVE feed (2.3 GB — by far the
# largest single item in the repository), MITRE ATT&CK, CWE, CAPEC raw
# downloads. The compiled/ JSONL distillations of all four are what ships.
Knowledge/intel_db/cve
Knowledge/intel_db/cwe
Knowledge/intel_db/capec
Knowledge/intel_db/attack

# Raw methodology PDFs (NIST/OWASP/PTES guides) — the compiled/ chunked
# JSONL is what the retrieval pipeline actually reads at runtime.
Knowledge/methodology_db/*.pdf

# Raw HTB legal/policy source PDFs — only policy_db/compiled/ is read by
# apex_host.policy.policy_loader at runtime.
Knowledge/policy_db/sources

# Archives, local caches/indexes, and OS artifacts that may exist locally
# under Knowledge/ but are never part of a clean checkout or the compiled
# output.
Knowledge/**/*.zip
Knowledge/**/*.tar
Knowledge/**/*.tar.gz
Knowledge/**/*.7z
Knowledge/**/*.gz
Knowledge/**/.cache
Knowledge/**/cache
Knowledge/**/*.faiss
Knowledge/**/*.idx
Knowledge/**/*.index
Knowledge/**/*.sqlite
Knowledge/**/*.db
Knowledge/**/*.tmp
Knowledge/**/.DS_Store

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Deliberately NOT excluded (documented so a future edit does not
# accidentally break the build):
#   pyproject.toml, uv.lock       — required for `uv sync --frozen`
#   memfabric/, apex_host/,
#   apex_tool_service/            — first-party source, required to build
#   Knowledge/*/compiled/         — explicitly COPYed by the Dockerfile
#   .python-version               — not excluded, but also not COPYed by
#                                    the Dockerfile (build uses the base
#                                    image's system Python directly via
#                                    UV_PYTHON_DOWNLOADS=never); harmless
#                                    either way since no COPY references it
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
